Map of Mouse and Human $\alpha \beta$ T Cell Development (Actually only mouse in this assignment)¶

The data analyzed in this assignment was accompanied by the following paper: Chopp et al., An Integrated Epigenomic and Transcriptomic Map of Mouse and HumanabT Cell Development,Immunity (2020), https://doi.org/10.1016/j.immuni.2020.10.024

The publication contains several sequencing data sets, which are listed below:

  • GSE148973 (RNAseq EXP1)
  • GSE148974 (RNAseq Exp2)
  • GSE148975 (Population ATACseq)
  • GSE148976 (Thpok ChIPSeq)
  • GSE148977 (Mouse scRNAseq)
  • GSE148978 (Human scRNAseq)
  • GSE148979 (Mouse scATACseq)
  • GSE148980 (Human scATACseq)
  • GSE157286 (ThpokKO scRNAseq)

In this assignment only the population ATAC sequencing data will be analyzed, printed in bold above and can be accessed here https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE148975 . In the screenshot below additional information on the individuals runs are listed, unfortunately no bigWig file or bed file is uploaded (yet). The publication is very recent.

   

Then the run IDs can be found in the SRA run selector view: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Traces/study/?acc=PRJNA626653&o=acc_s%3Aa. We can see that the Thpok gene is floxed in the mouse genome and that we have cells with an active CRE recombinase under the control of te CD4 promotor. This means CD4 positive cells will not have the Thpok gene in Cre positive mice. Via ATAC sequcning we can ivestigate the differences in open chromatin in CD4 cells but also in other cell types that might be impacted by this knockout. Then we see a 3rd cell type which are the double negatives (negative for both CD4 and CD8, this is a precursor T cell). Thpok is a CD4+-lineage transcription factor, anD4+ lineage commitment. Below an overview of the three cell types:

  • Thpok KO immature CD4SP thymocytes
  • WT immature CD4SP thymocytes
  • Unsignaled DP thymocytes

   

Finally we expect around 76 million reads per run from the example run below and accessed from herehttps://trace.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Traces/sra/?run=SRR11576073. We also conclude that the data is paired end.

 

The population ATAC data is based on 50.000 cells per sample and sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 (150bp paired-end). Note that only the nuclei were isolated and so no mtDNA was extracted but apparently this is imperfect and samtool was used to remove mtDNA contamination.The followig analysis pipeline was outlined in the publication:

  • ATACseq fastq files were trimmed with Trimmomatic
  • Aligned to mouse genome (mm10) using Bowtie2 (v2.3.4,X set to 2000)
  • Low quality (MAPQ < 30) and mitochondrial reads were removed with Samtools (v1.6)
  • Peaks were called using Macs2 (v2.2.4, pvalue 1e-7 andkeep-dup all)
  • Homer (4.10) for peak annotation and motif enrichment analyses

The paper is focussing mainly on the sincle cell data but one figure on the population ATAC sequencing at least made the supplementary material(S4D) as mentioned in the section on "Genomic and Transcriptomic Impacts of Thpok during CD4+ T Cell Differentiation":

(D)Population ATAC-seq was performed on wild-type orZbtb7b-deficient immature CD4+ SP thymocytes sorted asin Fig.S4A,and unsignaled wild-type DP thymocytes(CD4+CD8+CD69).Genome browser tracks show ATAC-seq signals at the Il2-Il21 gene locus.Representative of three biologicalreplicates per genotype.

One goal of this analasysis is to reproduce this figure and to try to add some more insight if time permits.

There were really a lot of reads mapped to the mitchondiral DNA: 11760773 I find this a bit weird, since the method they used was purifying nuclei and then there should already be less mitchondrial DNA if at al in the samples. However, there seems to be a problem of mtDNA contamination in general in ATAC sequencing.

Enriched motifs in the mice with wt Thpok in CD4+ cells¶

We see that in the wt we have enrichment for the Runx motif as claimed by the authors in CD4+ cells. This makes sense because Thpok binding to the DNA could make the DNA accesible for ATAC sequncing t regions where there are binding sites for Runx as well. This could mean that Thpok is there first and after Runx is recruited.

Enriched motifs in the mice with knock-out Thpok in CD4+ cells¶

We see that RUNX motif is enriched for the knock-out mice as well but in different cells not the CD4+ cells. Would that be compensation, or is just an artifact?

The peaks we called are near genes that are involved in immune processes for the KO sample. That is undoubtedly correct but quite superficial. Nevertheless it gives me more trust in the data analysis so far. Since these are the expected GO-terms (based on cond1).

The cond2 file did not lead to results, most likely due to the large number of peaks that were called more than in the KO condition. Thpok really seems to lead to a lot of open regions.

It would have been interesting to see which genes are more accesible in the presence of Thpok (so in the wt) compared to the KO to look at potential interaction partners but it is also interesting to look at the genes that seem to be more accesible in the KO. We will take this list from GREAT for the further analysis.

In [65]:
cat 20201218-public-4.0.4-JV5qVZ-mm10-GOBiologicalProcess-GO_0002376-region.txt | cut -f 1 | grep -v '#' > KOThpok-accesibleGenes-GREAT.txt

Thpok (Zbtb7b) is required to maintain the CD4+transcriptome but contrasting with this the expression of CD4+-signature genes in immature CD4+ SP thymocytes did not require Thpok (findings from RNA seq). ATAC-seq on CD4+SP thymocytes indicated that Thpok is dispensable for epigenomic opening of CD4-specific peaks, including at the Il2-Il21 locus. This challenges the idea thatThpok functions in thymocytes by promoting expression of Socs-family genes (Luckey et al., 2014). So the main finding in the paper was that there was not much change in the chromatin accessibility after KO of thpok for CD4+ lineage commitment, however, we see that there quite some genes related to immune system processesand leukocyte activation are more accessible after KO of Thpok. There is thus certainly still a lot to learn about the interaction of Thpok with other TFs, such as for example Runx3 for which some regions seem to be accessible in more cells when Thpok is knocked out, when looking at the GREAT results. However, RUNX3 is also described as interaction partner for Thpok (Zbtb7b), e.g. when using STRING:

In this analysis we could not find that peaks in the wt cells were more associated with CfBF (which is known to form dimers with Runx) regions than KO. We suspect that this is due to a genome wide data set that was used. I should have used a CD4+ specific set of CfBf regions and then I would expect that there are more peaks in the wt associated with CfbF than in the KO. This suspicion is substantiated when looking at the Homer results, which show that Runx is both associated with peaks from the KO as well as the wt. But in the wt we find this association in CD4+ cells and in the KO in HPC7 cells.
